passages.text: 2Q Beat w/ UO Global Inflection; Mgmt Follow-Up Takes; Overweight

URBN reported 2Q EPS of \(\) 1.58\(above Street\) \ \(1.47\) driven by \(+11.3\%\) revenue growth (above Street \(+9.3\%\) Y/Y) and gross margin expansion of \(+113\) bps Y/Y to \(37.6\%\) (above Street \(37.5\%\) ), partially offset by SG&A deleverage of 28bps Y/Y to \(26.0\%\) of sales (vs. Street \(25.8\%\) ), equating to operating margin expansion of \(+85\) bps Y/Y to \(11.6\%\) ( \( \text{Street} +4.6\%\) ), Anthropologie \(+5.7\%\) (vs. Street \(+5.6\%\) ), and UO brand \(+4.2\%\) ( \(> \text{Street} +1.9\%\) ) including UO North America July comps increasing "strong single digits" (i.e. high-single-digits by our work) led by regular-price comp momentum (notably in the digital channel), which has sustained into August/3QTD by our work.

Looking ahead, management outlined 3Q25 expectations for (i) + high-single-digit consolidated sales growth Y/Y (vs. Street \(+7.2\%\) ) including +mid-single-digit same-store-sales growth on a consolidated basis with +mid-single-digit growth across all 3 banners (above Street \(+3.4\%\) ), +mid-single-digit growth with wholesale, and +mid-double-digit growth in Nuyly, (ii) 3Q gross margin roughly Flat Y/Y (vs. Street \(+18\) bps Y/Y) as tariff headwinds are offset by occupancy leverage & lower product markdowns (noting UO has less opportunity on markdown recapture YOY in 3Q relative to 4Q), and (iii) SG&A expenses to deleverage YOY due to planned marketing reinvestments, which equates to 3Q EPS of \(\sim\) 1.18 by our math (= Street \(\) 1.18\$

- Importantly on 3QTD trends, CEO Hayne noted "success for all brands has continued August to date and we are planning to deliver high single-digit growth in total sales for Q3. Both consumer demand and our execution remain strong" with our work pointing to all 3 respective brands tracking "at least" in line with 3Q's +MSD% same-store-sales growth outlook.

- Regarding the full-year, our work points to an unchanged outlook of +MSD% Anthropologie comps (vs. Street \(+5.0\%\) ), +MSD% Free People comps (vs. Street \(+7.5\%\) ), and raised Core UO comps to +LSD-MSD% (above +LSD% price), with +MSD% comp growth expected through 2H25). Further, management raised FY25 gross margin expectations to +100bps expansion Y/Y (vs. +50-100bps Y/Y prior & Street +83bps Y/Y) supported by favorable occupancy leverage, lower product markdowns, and Nuyly leverage, despite embedding incremental tariff headwinds to 2H25 (= -75bps net headwind in 2H25 vs. -20bps headwind prior). This implies 4Q gross margins expected to increase +75-100bps YOY supported by markdown improvement YOY at the UO brand (w/ greater opportunity YOY in 4Q > 3Q) more than offsetting tariff headwinds, with management clarifying 4Q's net

URBN maintains three fashion-forward brands, strong ecommerce penetration, and a healthy real estate portfolio in key metro markets. We see a 5- pronged top/bottom- line growth flywheel supported by "core stability" at Anthro/FP brands, oppty to 3x the FP Movement revenue base vs. today, double- digit Nulty growth, and "self- help" UO comp opportunity under the refreshed merchandising/marketing direction of President Shea Jensen (effective as of Feb '24), and UO merchandise margin recapture multi- year, driving Mid- Teens(+) annual EPS growth. We rate URBN Overweight.
We raise our Dec '26 Price Target to \(\) 89\((vs. prior\) \ \(88\) ) based on 13x our FY27 EPS \(=\) URBN's 3- yr pre- pandemic average multiple).

tariff headwind is anticipated to only be \(\sim 20\) bps worse sequentially vs. 3Q within the 2H25 outlook for a - 75bps net tariff headwind. On expenses, management expects 2H25 SG&A \(\) growth to be aligned with sales growth, with 3Q deleverage on marketing reinvestments offset by 4Q expense leverage.

Model Implications: We model FY25 EPS of \(\) 5.25\(vs. Street\) \ \(4.96\) and FY26 EPS of \(\) 5.93\(vs. Street\) \ \(5.46\) . Remain Overweight raising our Dec '26 Price Target to \(\) 89\(based on 13x our FY27 EPS (= URBN's 3 - year pre - pandemic average).\)
Key Mgmt Follow- Up Takes & Model Implications:

\(\) 28M\(JPM e) increased +11.3\% and a Flat contribution to consolidated gross margins, and (iii) Nuyly Gross Profit\) \ \(s\) of \(\) 38M\(>JPM e\) \ \(37M\) increased \(+47\%\) Y/Y and drove \(+74\) bps to consolidated gross margins, with leverage on logistics expenses. Looking ahead, mgmt sees 3Q gross margin - Flat Y/Y at 36.5% (vs. Street 36.7%) with increased tariff costs (- 60bps by our estimates) offsetting occupancy leverage and markdown recapture at UO (with the 3Q YOY opportunity on markdowns less than 4Q's opportunity as inventories were tightly managed at UO exiting 2Q relative to product mis-execution in 4Q LY). To that end, management expects 4Q gross margin expansion of +75- 100bps Y/Y (vs. Street +5bps Y/Y) with a net tariff headwind of - 85bps by our estimates more than offset by store occupancy leverage & favorability on markdowns Y/Y at UO. This equates to a raised FY25 gross margins outlook of +100bps Y/Y (from 50- 100bps Y/Y prior).

- Balance Sheet Snapshot: URBn ended 2Q with \(\) 989M\(of cash and marketable securities with\) \ \(0M\) drawn down on the \(\) 350M\(asset backed line of credit facility. Total inventories finished up +15\% Y/Y (vs. 1Q +15\%)\), with wholesale inventories up +16\% (vs. +31\% 1Q) and retail segment inventories up +15\% (vs. 1Q +13\%), comprised of Anthro retail comparable inventories +16\% Y/Y (vs. 1Q 13\%), Free People +10\% Y/Y (vs. 1Q +23\%), and core UO inventories +3\% Y/Y (vs. 1Q +4\%). Looking ahead, mgmt increased FY25 Capex guidance to\) \ \(270M\) (from \(\) 240M\(prior) with 50\%\) tied to new stores, 25\% from technology and logistics investments, and 25\% from home office expansion.
